    <p>You can read the full text of the <a href="https://gdpr-info.eu">GDPR</a> on the GDPR official website.</p>

    <h3>Introduction</h3>

    <p>Delivering a great customer experience is one of our core values, and that includes protecting your privacy. HackerBay, Inc. and its affiliated companies and subsidiaries ("OneUptime", "we", "us") have established this privacy statement ("Privacy Statement") to help our customers, business partners, and visitors to our website, mobile applications, and any other location where we link to this policy ("Website") understand the information we collect, why we collect it, what we do with it, and the controls you have over it. We want you to feel informed and comfortable when you visit with us.</p>

    <p>Please read this Privacy Statement carefully. By using our Website, you agree to the collection, use, and disclosure of information as described here. If we make a material change to this Privacy Statement, we will provide reasonable advance notice — for example, by email to account holders or a prominent notice on the Website — before the change takes effect. Non-material changes (such as typo corrections or clarifications) will be posted with an updated revision date.</p>

    <h3>Who is responsible for your data</h3>
    <p>The data controller for information collected through this Website and our products is HackerBay, Inc. If you have questions, concerns, or wish to exercise any of the rights described below, you can reach our privacy team at <a href="mailto:privacy@oneuptime.com">privacy@oneuptime.com</a>. For GDPR-related matters, you can also contact our Data Protection Officer at the same address with "DPO" in the subject line.</p>

    <h3>Data Collection</h3>
    <p><strong>Information you provide to us.</strong> OneUptime collects information you choose to provide when you: apply for a job at OneUptime; download or install a product; request a quote; purchase or register a product; sign up for newsletters, support materials, white papers, or our email list; obtain support, services, or training; create a user account on our Website, customer portal, or community forum; or otherwise contact us. This information may include your name, address, email address, telephone number, username, password, information about the products you use, and payment information. If you use a third-party login (such as a social network), we may receive limited information from that service based on your settings there.</p>

    <p><strong>Information we may collect automatically.</strong> We may use cookies, web beacons, web analytics, and similar technologies to collect information about your device and how you use the Website or our products. These may be first-party tools (hosted on a OneUptime domain) or third-party tools. See the Cookies section below for details.</p>

    <p><strong>Information from other sources.</strong> We may obtain information about you from other sources, such as updated contact information and publicly available data, and may combine it with information we already hold in order to keep records accurate.</p>

    <p><strong>Real User Monitoring ("RUM").</strong> OneUptime provides a Real User Monitoring service that allows our customers to understand how visitors interact with their own websites. When a visitor loads a page that includes our RUM code, that code sends information (such as page load timing, browser type, and actions on the page) to OneUptime. In this service, <em>our customer is the data controller</em> and OneUptime acts as a <em>data processor</em> on their behalf — we process Visitor Data only on our customer's instructions and under a Data Processing Agreement. Our customers are responsible for providing notice to and obtaining any required consent from their visitors. We do not use Visitor Data to build profiles for our own purposes, and we do not sell it. Where Visitor Data is used for aggregated analytics, it is anonymized so that individuals cannot be re-identified.</p>

    <h3>Our Commitment to GDPR</h3>
    <p>The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) and the UK GDPR regulate the processing of personal data of individuals in the EU, EEA, and UK. These laws apply to us because we serve customers in those regions. We have made information security and data privacy foundational principles of our business, and we are committed to ongoing GDPR and UK GDPR compliance.</p>

    <% if (section === "privacy") { %>
    <p>You can read more about our <a href="/legal/gdpr">GDPR policy here</a>.</p>
    <% } %>

    <h3>Data Use</h3>
    <p>We use the information we collect to:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Administer and operate the OneUptime products, services, and Website — including completing transactions, providing support, responding to your requests, preventing fraud, and communicating with you about your account.</li>
        <li>Send you marketing communications about OneUptime, our products, and our partners — but only where we have a lawful basis to do so. In the EU, EEA, and UK, marketing emails are opt-in, and you can withdraw consent at any time.</li>
        <li>Research, develop, and improve the Website and our products.</li>
        <li>Protect the security and integrity of the Website, our products, and our business.</li>
        <li>Comply with legal obligations.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>We rely on the following legal bases under the GDPR: performance of a contract with you, your consent, our legitimate interests (where not overridden by your rights), and compliance with legal obligations.</p>

    <h3>Data Sharing</h3>
    <p>We may share the information we collect:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>With vetted third-party service providers and sub-processors who help us operate our Website and deliver our products (hosting, payment processing, customer support, email delivery, analytics). A current list of our sub-processors is available at <a href="/legal/sub-processors">our sub-processors page</a>, and we will provide advance notice of material changes where required.</li>
        <li>In response to lawful requests from law enforcement or government authorities, a subpoena, or other legal process — we review each request and only disclose what is legally required.</li>
        <li>Where we reasonably believe disclosure is necessary to protect OneUptime, our customers, or the public from harm or fraud.</li>
        <li>With your consent, or as otherwise described to you at the point of collection.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>We may also share aggregated or anonymized statistics that do not identify any individual or company. <strong>OneUptime does not sell or rent your personal information</strong>, and we will not share your personal information with others except as described in this Privacy Statement.</p>

    <p><strong>Business transfers.</strong> If OneUptime is involved in a merger, acquisition, reorganization, or sale of assets, your information may be transferred as part of that transaction. We will notify affected account holders by email before any such transfer takes effect, and the transferee will be required to honor this Privacy Statement (or provide equivalent protections) with respect to your personal information.</p>

    <h3>Data Storage and International Transfers</h3>
    <p>OneUptime operates globally, and using our Website and products involves the transmission and storage of data across borders. Your personal information may be stored on servers in — or processed by staff located in — countries outside your country of residence, including outside the European Economic Area (EEA) and the UK.</p>

    <p>When we transfer personal data out of the EEA, UK, or Switzerland to a country that has not received an adequacy decision, we rely on appropriate safeguards such as the European Commission's <strong>Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs)</strong>, the UK International Data Transfer Addendum, or equivalent mechanisms. You can request a copy of the safeguards we have in place by emailing <a href="mailto:privacy@oneuptime.com">privacy@oneuptime.com</a>.</p>

    <h3>How Long We Keep Your Data</h3>
    <p>We keep personal data only as long as necessary for the purposes for which it was collected, to comply with legal, tax, and accounting obligations, and to resolve disputes or enforce our agreements. As general guidance:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Account data</strong> (name, email, login credentials): retained while your account is active, and for up to 90 days after closure to allow for recovery, after which it is deleted or anonymized.</li>
        <li><strong>Billing and tax records</strong>: retained for up to 7 years as required by tax and accounting law.</li>
        <li><strong>Product telemetry and logs</strong>: retained for up to 90 days in operational systems; longer in aggregated, anonymized form.</li>
        <li><strong>Support communications</strong>: retained for up to 3 years after the last interaction.</li>
        <li><strong>Marketing preferences</strong>: retained until you withdraw consent, and for a short period afterward to honor the opt-out.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Retention periods for customer-controlled data (including RUM Visitor Data) are configured by our customers in their OneUptime account.</p>

    <h3>Your Rights</h3>
    <p>You have the following rights regarding your personal information. These rights are granted under the GDPR and UK GDPR to individuals in the EU, EEA, and UK, and we extend most of them to all users regardless of location.</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Right of access</strong> — request a copy of the personal data we hold about you.</li>
        <li><strong>Right to rectification</strong> — ask us to correct inaccurate or incomplete data.</li>
        <li><strong>Right to erasure ("right to be forgotten")</strong> — ask us to delete your personal data.</li>
        <li><strong>Right to restrict processing</strong> — ask us to limit how we use your data.</li>
        <li><strong>Right to data portability</strong> — receive your data in a structured, machine-readable format, or have it transferred to another controller.</li>
        <li><strong>Right to object</strong> — object to processing based on our legitimate interests, and opt out of direct marketing at any time.</li>
        <li><strong>Right to withdraw consent</strong> — where we rely on consent, you may withdraw it at any time without affecting prior processing.</li>
        <li><strong>Right not to be subject to automated decision-making</strong> that produces legal or similarly significant effects.</li>
        <li><strong>Right to lodge a complaint</strong> with your local data protection supervisory authority.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>To exercise any of these rights, email us at <a href="mailto:privacy@oneuptime.com">privacy@oneuptime.com</a> or use the in-product privacy controls in your account settings. We will respond within <strong>30 days</strong> (extendable by up to two further months for complex requests, with notice to you). Exercising your rights is free of charge; in the rare case a request is manifestly unfounded or excessive, we may charge a reasonable fee or decline, and we will explain why.</p>

    <p>We may need to verify your identity before fulfilling a request in order to protect your data. We may decline a request only where permitted by law — for example, where fulfilling it would infringe the rights and freedoms of others, or where we have an overriding legal obligation to retain the data. If we decline, we will tell you why and explain your right to complain.</p>

    <h3>California Residents (CCPA / CPRA)</h3>
    <p>If you are a California resident, you have the following rights under the California Consumer Privacy Act, as amended by the California Privacy Rights Act:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>The right to know what personal information we collect, use, disclose, and (if applicable) sell or share.</li>
        <li>The right to delete personal information we have collected from you.</li>
        <li>The right to correct inaccurate personal information.</li>
        <li>The right to opt out of the sale or sharing of personal information.</li>
        <li>The right to limit the use of sensitive personal information.</li>
        <li>The right to non-discrimination for exercising your rights.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>OneUptime does not sell your personal information</strong>, and we do not share it for cross-context behavioral advertising as those terms are defined under the CCPA/CPRA. To exercise any California right, email <a href="mailto:privacy@oneuptime.com">privacy@oneuptime.com</a>. You may also designate an authorized agent to make a request on your behalf.</p>

    <h3>Cookies</h3>
    <p>Cookies are small text files placed on your device when you visit a website. We use cookies and similar technologies to keep you signed in, remember your preferences, understand how the Website is used, and improve our products.</p>
    <p>We use the following categories of cookies:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Strictly necessary</strong> — required for the Website to function (e.g. authentication, load balancing). These cannot be disabled.</li>
        <li><strong>Functional</strong> — remember your preferences and choices.</li>
        <li><strong>Analytics</strong> — help us understand how visitors use the Website so we can improve it.</li>
        <li><strong>Marketing</strong> — used only with your consent, to measure the effectiveness of our marketing.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>You can manage cookies through the cookie banner on our Website or through your browser settings. Disabling strictly necessary cookies may affect how the Website works. For details, see our <a href="/legal/cookies">Cookie Policy</a>.</p>

    <h3>Audit Rights</h3>
    <h4>1. Purpose</h4>
    <p>This Customer Audit Rights Policy outlines the rights of our customers to audit our processing of their personal data under the GDPR, and reflects our commitment to transparency and accountability.</p>

    <h4>2. Scope</h4>
    <p>This policy applies to all customers whose personal data we process, whether collected directly from them or obtained from other sources.</p>

    <h4>3. Customer Audit Rights</h4>
    <p>Customers have the right to request an audit of the processing activities we carry out concerning their personal data. The following provisions apply:</p>

    <h5>3.1. How to request an audit</h5>
    <p>Send a written audit request to our Data Protection Officer at <a href="mailto:privacy@oneuptime.com">privacy@oneuptime.com</a> with "DPO — Audit Request" in the subject line. The request should set out the purpose and scope of the audit.</p>

    <h5>3.2. Audit scope and timing</h5>
    <p>We will acknowledge audit requests within 10 business days and work with you in good faith to agree on a reasonable scope and timing, taking into account the complexity of the request and the confidentiality of other customers' data.</p>

    <h5>3.3. Audit methodology</h5>
    <p>Audits are conducted in a way that protects the confidentiality and integrity of personal data and other proprietary information. The methodology may include reviews of documentation, interviews, site visits, or other reasonable methods appropriate to the scope.</p>

    <h5>3.4. Third-party auditors</h5>
    <p>You may engage an independent third-party auditor, provided they are bound by appropriate confidentiality obligations and comply with the GDPR.</p>

    <h5>3.5. Audit findings and reporting</h5>
    <p>Upon completion, we will share a summary of findings, including any identified compliance gaps or areas for improvement, within a reasonable timeframe.</p>

    <h5>3.6. Corrective actions</h5>
    <p>If the audit identifies non-compliance or deficiencies, we will take appropriate corrective action promptly — for example, implementing additional safeguards, updating policies, or providing additional staff training.</p>

    <h4>4. Confidentiality and Security</h4>
    <p>All audit-related information, including personal data reviewed during the audit, is treated as strictly confidential and in compliance with applicable data protection laws. We maintain appropriate technical and organizational measures to safeguard confidentiality, integrity, and security throughout.</p>

    <h4>5. Policy Review</h4>
    <p>We review this Customer Audit Rights Policy periodically and update it as needed to stay aligned with the GDPR and other applicable laws.</p>

    <h4>6. Contact</h4>
    <p>For questions about this policy or to submit an audit request, contact our Data Protection Officer at <a href="mailto:privacy@oneuptime.com">privacy@oneuptime.com</a>.</p>

    <h3>Confidentiality and Security — Technical and Organizational Measures</h3>
    <p>All personal data we process is protected by a layered set of technical and organizational measures designed to meet GDPR requirements:</p>

    <h4>1. Data Encryption</h4>
    <p>We use strong, industry-standard encryption to protect personal data both in transit and at rest, preventing unauthorized access and preserving integrity.</p>

    <h4>2. Access Control</h4>
    <p>Access to personal data is limited to authorized personnel under the principle of least privilege — staff only receive the access required for their role.</p>

    <h4>3. Employee Training and Awareness</h4>
    <p>We run regular training and awareness programs so that our team understands their data protection obligations and the practical steps required to keep data safe.</p>

    <h4>4. Incident Response and Breach Management</h4>
    <p>We maintain an incident response and breach management process covering proactive monitoring, detection, response planning, and timely notification to supervisory authorities and affected individuals where required by the GDPR (within 72 hours of becoming aware of a reportable breach).</p>

    <h4>5. Regular Security Audits and Assessments</h4>
    <p>We carry out regular internal and independent third-party security audits and assessments to identify vulnerabilities, assess risk, and validate the effectiveness of our controls.</p>

    <h4>6. Data Minimization and Retention</h4>
    <p>We collect only the personal data we need, keep it only as long as necessary (see "How Long We Keep Your Data" above), and securely dispose of data that is no longer required.</p>

    <h4>7. Vendor Management</h4>
    <p>Third-party vendors and sub-processors with access to personal data are vetted for their privacy and security practices, bound by contract (including GDPR-required terms), and monitored for ongoing compliance.</p>

    <h4>8. Confidentiality</h4>
    <p>All OneUptime employees sign a confidentiality agreement as part of onboarding and remain bound by it for the duration of, and after, their employment.</p>

    <h3>Marketing Choices</h3>
    <p>We may occasionally send you emails about OneUptime, our products, or our partners — either with your consent (where required) or on the basis of an existing customer relationship. If you no longer wish to receive these emails, click the <strong>"unsubscribe"</strong> link at the bottom of any marketing email, change your preferences in your account settings, or email us at <a href="mailto:privacy@oneuptime.com">privacy@oneuptime.com</a>. We will honor opt-out requests promptly, and in any case within 10 business days. Opting out of marketing will not affect transactional or service-related emails (for example, billing notices or security alerts).</p>

    <h3>Public Forums</h3>
    <p>Anything you post in community forums or other public areas of the Website ("User Contribution") is public information, and you are solely responsible for what you choose to share. Please be cautious about disclosing personal information in these areas — we cannot control who accesses it, and even after removal, content may remain in cached or archived copies, or may have been copied by others. OneUptime is not responsible for third-party circumvention of privacy settings on the Website. Report any suspected violations to <a href="mailto:privacy@oneuptime.com">privacy@oneuptime.com</a>.</p>

    <h3>Third-Party Sites</h3>
    <p>Our Website may include links to third-party websites for your convenience. OneUptime does not own or control these sites and is not responsible for their availability, content, or data practices. This Privacy Statement does not apply to information you provide to third parties. We encourage you to review the privacy policy of any third-party service before submitting information to it.</p>

    <h3>How to Update and Access Information</h3>
    <p>You can update most account information directly in your profile settings. To exercise any of the rights described under "Your Rights" above — including access, correction, deletion, or data portability — email us at <a href="mailto:privacy@oneuptime.com">privacy@oneuptime.com</a>. You do not need to use a specific subject line; a plain-language request is fine.</p>

    <h3>Security</h3>
    <p>We use commercially reasonable security measures — including physical access controls, encryption, firewalls, network monitoring, and continuous security testing — to protect information you submit. No method of electronic transmission or storage is 100% secure, but we work hard to reduce risk and respond quickly if something goes wrong. If we become aware of a personal data breach affecting you, we will notify you and the relevant supervisory authorities as required by law.</p>

    <h3>Children</h3>
    <p>Our Website and products are not directed to children. We do not knowingly collect personal information from children under <strong>16</strong> in the EU, EEA, and UK, or under <strong>13</strong> in the United States and other jurisdictions where 13 is the applicable threshold. If you believe we may hold information about a child below the applicable age, please contact <a href="mailto:privacy@oneuptime.com">privacy@oneuptime.com</a> and we will delete it promptly.</p>

    <h3>How to Contact the Supervisory Authorities</h3>
    <p>If you are in the EU, EEA, or UK and believe we have not adequately addressed a privacy concern, you have the right to lodge a complaint with your local data protection authority. A list of EU/EEA authorities is available at <a href="https://edpb.europa.eu/about-edpb/about-edpb/members_en">edpb.europa.eu</a>, and UK residents can contact the <a href="https://ico.org.uk">Information Commissioner's Office (ICO)</a>. We would, however, appreciate the chance to address your concerns directly first — please reach out to us at <a href="mailto:privacy@oneuptime.com">privacy@oneuptime.com</a>.</p>

    <h3>Questions</h3>
    <p>If you have any questions about this Privacy Statement or our data handling practices, email us at <a href="mailto:privacy@oneuptime.com">privacy@oneuptime.com</a>. To help us respond, please include enough detail about your question or request. We may need to contact you for additional information.</p>

    <h3>Modifications to this Privacy Statement</h3>
    <p>We may update this Privacy Statement from time to time and will note the date of its most recent revision at the top. If we update or modify this Privacy Statement in a material way, we will provide reasonable advance notice — for example, by email to account holders or a prominent notice on the Website — before the change takes effect, so you have an opportunity to review it and, if you disagree, to close your account or withdraw your consent.</p>
</section>
